Getting started

Annie Visser-Quinn & Melissa Bedinger

In this vignette, you will install everything you need to get started with AHgen:

  • Step 1 - Install R and RStudio
  • Step 2 - Install the required R packages
  • Step 3 - Install AHgen from a GitHub repository

Each step is detailed via the tabs below.

Install guide

Step 1 - Install R & RStudio

What is R?

R is an open source (free) programming language used to develop statistical software.

What is RStudio?

RStudio is an integrated development environment for R. In simpler terms, RStudio provides a more user-friendly environment to run R code from. It is also open source and highly recommended.

How do I install R & RStudio?

The screenshots below will guide you through the process of downloading R and RStudio. Note that the versions of R and RStudio shown in the screenshots below will now be outdated; please download the most recent version.








Step 2 - Install R packages

What is an R package?

An R package is a collection of functions and/or data that have been packaged together. For more information, check out this guide.

Packages to install other packages

There are many ways to install R packages. In example AHgen scripts, there are two packages which are used for the specific purpose of installing other packages. We find these two packages make the application of AHgen smoother.

  • devtools - This package makes package development easier by providing R functions that simplify and expedite common tasks. The install_github() function is used in example AHgen scripts, to install a package straight from GitHub. This is useful if a package is not yet hosted on CRAN (such as AHgen), or if you want to play with a different branch of a package (e.g.the newest development version).
  • pacman - This package is an R package management tool that combines the functionality of base library related functions into intuitively named functions. The p_load() function is used in example AHgen scripts, to load multiple packages at the same time instead of using the library() function. Any packages in the p_load() function will also be installed if you have not already done so; this acts as an extra check.

AHgen dependencies

AHgen uses some functions from base R which do not require you to install any additional packages. In particular, AHgen uses base, grid, grDevices, and stats.

AHgen also relies on functions in several other pre-existing packages. These are called dependencies.

Dependencies

  • the tidyverse is actually a collection of R packages designed for data science. All packages share an underlying design philosophy, grammar, and data structures.

  • Biobase and BiocManager implements base functions for Bioconductor. It has a helpful function called subListExtract() to extract the same element from the sublists of a list. For example, if outputs of AHgen are in list format, and every AHgen output has a list element called vertices, the subListExtract() function can extract the list element vertices from multiple lists quickly. This is useful for comparing AHgen outputs. To install Biobase you will first need to install the package BiocManager. This package serves as the primary way to ensure that the appropriate Biobase installation is used with respect to the version of R in use, regardless of the R and Bioconductor release cycles.

  • data.table provides a high-performance version of base Rs data.frame, with syntax and feature enhancements for ease of use, convenience and programming speed.

  • igraph provides routines for simple graphs and network analysis.

  • installr offers a set of R functions for the installation and updating of software.

  • janitor provides simple functions for examining and cleaning dirty data.

  • xlsx provides R functions to read, write, and format Excel files.

  • ggh4x, gginnards, ggraph, ggrepel, and scales are all ggplot2 extension packages to customise visualisations.

  • plotly helps to create interactive web graphics via the open source JavaScript graphing library plotly.js.

  • see provides plotting utilities supporting packages in the easystats ecosystem and some extra themes, geoms, and scales for ggplot2

  • sf provides support for simple features, a standardized way to encode spatial vector data.

  • tidytext provides functions and supporting data sets to allow conversion of text to and from tidy formats, and to switch seamlessly between tidy tools and existing text mining packages.

Some packages are needed to borrow only a single function; other packages are heavily relied upon. For more detail on dependencies you can see AHgen/data-raw/functionsTracker_20230707.xlsx.

Install R packages

To install devtools and pacman:

  1. Open RStudio.
  2. Paste install.packages(c("devtools", "pacman")) into the console (bottom left hand side).
  3. Press enter.

It should look something like below.



To install BiocManager and Biobase, use the following code.

# Install BiocManager and Biobase 
# Following instructions from https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/Biobase.html

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
install.packages("BiocManager")
BiocManager::install("Biobase")

To install the rest of the dependencies, use the following code.

# Install AHgen dependencies
pacman::p_load(tidyverse, data.table, igraph, installr, janitor, 
               ggh4x, gginnards, ggraph, ggrepel, scales, 
               plotly, see, sf, tidytext)


Step 3 - Install AHgen

To install the AHgen package itself, use the following code.

The argument dependencies = TRUE will include installation of any AHgen dependencies i.e.supporting packages - in case they have not already been installed.

devtools::install_github("avisserquinn/AHgen", dependencies = TRUE)

And youre ready to go!

If you want to explore, load the AHgen package.

pacman::p_load(AHgen)

See a full list of its current functions.
